{"title_page": "Premio Herralde", "text_new": "The '''Premio Herralde''' is a [[Spain|Spanish]] [[literary prize]]. It is awarded annually by the publishing house [[Anagrama]] to an original novel in the Spanish language. Established in 1983, the prize takes its name from [[Jorge Herralde]], founder of Anagrama. Accompanied by a cash prize, the award is announced every year in November. \n\n== List of winners ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year || Author || Country || Title\n|-\n| 1983 || [[\u00c1lvaro Pombo]] || {{ESP}} || ''El h\u00e9roe de las mansardas de Mansard''\n|-\n| 1984 || [[Sergio Pitol]] || {{MEX}} || ''El desfile del amor''\n|-\n| 1985 || [[Adelaida Garc\u00eda Morales]] || {{ESP}} || ''El silencio de las sirenas''\n|-\n| 1986 || [[Javier Mar\u00edas]] || {{ESP}} || ''El hombre sentimental''\n|-\n| 1987 || [[F\u00e9lix de Az\u00faa]] || {{ESP}} || ''Diario de un hombre humillado''\n|-\n| 1988 || [[Vicente Molina Foix]] || {{ESP}} || ''La Quincena Sovi\u00e9tica''\n|-\n| 1989 || [[Miguel S\u00e1nchez-Ostiz]] || {{ESP}} || ''La gran ilusi\u00f3n''\n|-\n| 1990 || [[Justo Navarro]] || {{ESP}} || ''Accidentes \u00edntimos''\n|-\n| 1991 || [[Javier Garc\u00eda S\u00e1nchez]] || {{ESP}} || ''La historia m\u00e1s triste''\n|-\n| 1992 || [[Paloma D\u00edaz-Mas]] || {{ESP}} || ''El sue\u00f1o de Venecia''\n|-\n| 1993 || [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Riera de Leyva]] || {{ESP}} || ''Aves de paso''\n|-\n| 1994 <br/>[[ex aequo]] || [[Pedro Zarraluki]]<br/>[[Carlos Perell\u00f3n]] || {{ESP}}<br/>{{ESP}} || ''La historia del silencio''<br/>''La ciudad doble''\n|-\n| 1995 || [[Jos\u00e9 \u00c1ngel Gonz\u00e1lez Sainz]] || {{ESP}} || ''Un mundo exasperado''\n|-\n| 1996 || [[Antonio Soler (writer)|Antonio Soler]] || {{ESP}} || ''Las bailarinas muertas''\n|-\n| 1997 || [[Jaime Bayly]] || {{PER}} || ''La noche es virgen''\n|-\n| 1998 || [[Roberto Bola\u00f1o]] || {{CHI}} || ''[[Los detectives salvajes]]''\n|-\n| 1999 || [[Marcos Giralt Torrente]] || {{ESP}} || ''Par\u00